english:
  title: A Libation for Minister Lee Gwang-jeong
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day of this month and year, I, [name and title], humbly present this offering of delicacies and clear wine in libation to the spirit of the Minister-in-Waiting and Chancellor Lee.

    Human fortune is a thing rarely complete. Pursue honor alone and you are constrained—joy never reaches its fullness. Seek only joy and you become dissolute—honor grows thin as gossamer. It is like a tiger without wings. Yet our Master alone held both in perfect measure.

    When he rode forth as general, the leopard-skin palanquin gleamed and crimson banners flew. When he returned to serve as minister, jade pendants hung and golden gates stood open. In both the glory of commander and statesman, you alone were graced. In your home, beauties fair as arched brows lined the chambers, adorned each day with pearls and jade, their fingers dancing on stringed instruments. Even when you laid aside your office in age, your vigor remained undiminished, your love of pleasure as keen as in your youth.

    You would say to your children: "Life flickers like a floating cloud—I shall not burden you with my wishes. Bring swiftly to my table the hunt's fresh bounty." In simple garments you wandered freely from place to place. In this alone has a man's joy found its perfect expression—and you perfected it.

    I remember the trials of old, when I endured cruel hardship—hiding like a rabbit, crouching like a mouse, stripped of all refuge. It was by your grace alone that I reached this day. Each time the memory returns, sorrow shakes me suddenly.

    Alas! I revered you as father, your sister as mother. Now that you have passed beyond, it is as though I have lost my father. What words suffice for this farewell? Accept this single cup of humble wine—let it bring you peace, and comfort to my grieving heart.
  footnotes:
    - This is a spirit-offering text (祭文), a formal ceremonial composition presented at a memorial service to honor the deceased. The blank "on this day" and unnamed speaker reflect the template nature of such official documents.
    - The imagery of the tiger without wings (虎不傅以翼) is a classical reference meaning that even perfect creatures cannot have everything—yet Lee Gwang-jeong transcended this natural limitation.
    - The 'leopard-skin palanquin' and 'jade pendants with golden gates' are symbols of military and civil authority respectively, representing the rare achievement of excellence in both roles.
    - Lee Gyu-bo is speaking of his own survival during the Mongol invasions of Goryeo, for which he credits Lee Gwang-jeong's protection and support.
